{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 04:51:36.689955", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Enterprise network troubleshooting diagnosis report\\n\\nSummary of health\\n- Routing/Reachability: End-to-end IP connectivity across host subnets and the server farm is broadly healthy. Cross-subnet pings show 0% loss with typical RTTs around 2–4 ms.\\n- Web access: Direct HTTP access by IP to server farm nodes (e.g., 10.200.0.3) is fast (sub-10 ms connects). However, web access via DNS names (web0.local, web99.local) experiences approximately 1 second extra latency per request during name resolution.\\n- DHCP: Hosts have valid addresses in the expected 10.<core>.<dist>.0/24 ranges, indicating the DHCP/relay chain is functioning.\\n\\nDetected anomaly\\n- Severe, consistent latency specifically to/from the DNS server (10.200.0.2).\\n  - From multiple vantage points (hosts and servers), ICMP RTTs to dns_server are ~1001–1005 ms per reply.\\n  - Example: host_1_1_1_1 → dns_server: 4/4 replies, RTT ~1003 ms each.\\n  - dns_server → hosts: 4/4 replies, RTT ~1003–1005 ms each.\\n\\nImpact observed\\n- DNS lookup delay seen by clients:\\n  - Curl timing from host_1_1_1_1:\\n    - http://web99.local: namelookup ≈ 1.00 s; total ≈ 2.08–2.23 s.\\n    - http://web0.local: namelookup ≈ 1.00 s; total ≈ 2.13–2.32 s.\\n    - http://10.200.0.3 (by IP): namelookup ≈ 0 s; connect ≈ 0–85 ms; totals ≈ 1.12–2.33 s (no DNS delay component).\\n  - The ≈1.0 s name lookup penalty directly corresponds to the DNS server’s interface delay.\\n\\nLocalization of the fault\\n- Device: dns_server\\n- Interface: eth0 (10.200.0.2/24)\\n- Evidence of induced delay:\\n  - tc/qdisc on dns_server eth0: qdisc netem … delay 1s\\n    - Command output: “qdisc netem 8061: root refcnt 2 limit 1000 delay 1s”\\n  - Server access router interfaces (eth0/eth6) show default fq_codel only, no artificial delay.\\n  - ICMP behavior consistent with egress delay on dns_server’s eth0: replies from dns_server incur ~1 s; requests to dns_server also measure ~1 s because the echo reply is delayed.\\n\\nOther relevant findings\\n- DNS service state and sockets:\\n  - named.service: active (running).\\n  - bind9.service: inactive (unused).\\n  - netstat indicates named listening on 10.200.0.2:53 and on 127.0.0.1:53.\\n  - DNS service itself is reachable; only latency is abnormal.\\n- Server farm reachability:\\n  - load_balancer (10.200.0.7): host_1_1_1_1 ping RTT ~2–5 ms; normal.\\n  - Web servers (10.200.0.3–.6): normal network RTTs when accessed directly.\\n- OSPF/routing plane: No packet loss in cross-area pings; latency patterns normal except when traffic involves dns_server.\\n\\nRoot cause\\n- An artificial 1-second traffic control delay (tc netem delay 1s) configured on dns_server’s eth0 is introducing ~1 s of additional latency for all traffic egressing the DNS server. This directly degrades DNS response times network-wide, causing slow name resolution and inflated end-to-end web access times when services are accessed by hostname.\\n\\nScope of impact\\n- All clients using the internal DNS server (10.200.0.2) for name resolution.\\n- All DNS lookups and any traffic sourced from dns_server are affected by ≈1 s added delay per exchange.\\n- Other services and routing remain healthy; the issue is isolated to the DNS server’s interface queuing configuration., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='6e4ae901-3e55-4e3d-8f46-6a001e6ec61f'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
